Tell me what to do.

262
00:20:19,740 --> 00:20:22,395
Well, talk to him,
Confront him with it.

263
00:20:22,438 --> 00:20:23,657
I can't.

264
00:20:23,700 --> 00:20:24,701
Why?

265
00:20:26,268 --> 00:20:28,227
I'm afraid he might leave.

266
00:20:28,270 --> 00:20:30,446
If he leaves I don't know
what I'd do.

267
00:20:30,490 --> 00:20:33,101
Pat, stop that.

268
00:20:33,144 --> 00:20:36,800
Listen,
you're holding on to something
that doesn't exist.

269
00:20:36,844 --> 00:20:38,846
This man isn't yours anymore.

270
00:20:41,544 --> 00:20:42,545
Why should he be?

271
00:20:43,372 --> 00:20:45,766
Look at me. [GASPS]

272
00:20:45,809 --> 00:20:46,854
I'm a mess.

273
00:20:48,072 --> 00:20:49,160
Honey...

274
00:20:50,510 --> 00:20:51,772
Maybe if I...

275
00:20:53,034 --> 00:20:55,906
If I fixed up a little,

276
00:20:55,950 --> 00:20:57,038
you know,

277
00:20:57,081 --> 00:20:59,649
put some makeup on
and fixed my hair.

278
00:20:59,693 --> 00:21:01,564
-Made really nice dinner.
-Pat stop.

279
00:21:01,608 --> 00:21:06,656
Stop it.
Pat, romance and makeup
are not going to fix this.

280
00:21:08,092 --> 00:21:10,530
You're not the
problem, Pat. He is.

281
00:21:13,663 --> 00:21:15,143
Aww.

282
00:21:17,580 --> 00:21:20,714
[CLOCK TICKING]

283
00:21:23,543 --> 00:21:25,414
[DOOR OPENS]

284
00:21:32,987 --> 00:21:34,162
Where have you been?

285
00:21:44,564 --> 00:21:47,306
Don't you never ever
ask me where I've been.

286
00:21:47,349 --> 00:21:48,611
You understand me?

287
00:21:48,655 --> 00:21:51,353
-You do not have the right to...
-I am your wife.

288
00:21:51,397 --> 00:21:54,313
-I have the right...
-You have the right to nothing!

289
00:21:55,879 --> 00:21:58,752
Because you do not own me, Pat.

290
00:21:58,795 --> 00:22:00,275
I guess not.

291
00:22:01,798 --> 00:22:04,148
Not judging from these...

292
00:22:04,192 --> 00:22:07,151
I found them in your jacket.

293
00:22:07,195 --> 00:22:10,329
We are barely getting by,
and you spend our money
like that!

294
00:22:15,638 --> 00:22:16,857
Tommy.

295
00:22:20,339 --> 00:22:21,949
Tommy.

296
00:22:23,124 --> 00:22:24,517
[KNOCKING AT DOOR]

297
00:22:25,909 --> 00:22:27,737
-Hi!
-Hi.

298
00:22:28,956 --> 00:22:31,698
It's kind of hard. Um...

299
00:22:31,741 --> 00:22:35,092
Could I borrow some cereal,
and maybe some milk

300
00:22:35,136 --> 00:22:36,877
-from you?
-Of course. Come on in.

301
00:22:36,920 --> 00:22:38,966
No, no.

302
00:22:39,009 --> 00:22:41,534
I just haven't been able
to get to the store.

303
00:22:42,926 --> 00:22:44,841
Why? What's the matter?

304
00:22:47,278 --> 00:22:51,413
Tommy went out for some cereal,
and he hasn't been home for
a couple of days.

305
00:22:51,457 --> 00:22:54,329
-[PATSY SIGHS]
-Don't you say another word.

306
00:22:55,374 --> 00:22:56,723
Tommy...

307
00:22:56,766 --> 00:22:58,202
PATSY: Tommy!

308
00:22:58,246 --> 00:23:02,337
[BABY CRYING]
-Hi, angel.
-Tommy, Tommy, honey.

309
00:23:02,859 --> 00:23:04,034
Talk to me.

310
00:23:04,078 --> 00:23:06,123
Tommy, just talk to me.

311
00:23:07,211 --> 00:23:09,170
[BABY CRYING]

312
00:23:09,213 --> 00:23:11,694
Tommy, please don't.
Don't do this.

313
00:23:12,434 --> 00:23:14,567
Don't... Don't leave us.

314
00:23:15,698 --> 00:23:17,526
Tommy.

315
00:23:17,570 --> 00:23:20,747
I'm sorry. I'll... I'll do
anything you want me to do.

316
00:23:20,790 --> 00:23:23,924
I'll be anything you want me to
be. Just don't do this.

317
00:23:23,967 --> 00:23:25,099
Don't leave.

318
00:23:25,142 --> 00:23:26,143
Please don't.

319
00:23:26,883 --> 00:23:28,842
Tommy, just don't

320
00:23:28,885 --> 00:23:32,889
leave us. Please,
honey, don't do it.

321
00:23:32,933 --> 00:23:34,674
I... Honey, don't.

322
00:23:35,022 --> 00:23:36,066
Tommy!

323
00:23:36,110 --> 00:23:37,720
Tommy, no!

324
00:23:37,764 --> 00:23:39,113
No!

325
00:23:39,156 --> 00:23:43,117
No! [GASPING]

326
00:23:43,160 --> 00:23:46,729
-No! You can't leave us!
-[BABY CRYING]

327
00:23:46,773 --> 00:23:48,992
[PATSY SOBBING]

328
00:23:49,689 --> 00:23:52,082
[ANDREA CRYING]

329
00:24:02,441 --> 00:24:04,443
[ANDREA KEEPS CRYING]

330
00:24:15,149 --> 00:24:18,674
-Please get up, mommy.
-Oh.

331
00:24:22,286 --> 00:24:23,766
[DOORBELL CHIMING]

332
00:24:29,119 --> 00:24:30,120
Hi, Pat.

333
00:24:30,686 --> 00:24:31,687
Where's Tommy?

334
00:24:32,471 --> 00:24:34,429
Tommy? I haven't seen him.

335
00:24:34,473 --> 00:24:36,649
His car's right there
in the driveway, Bill.

336
00:24:37,954 --> 00:24:39,521
I know he's here.

337
00:24:39,565 --> 00:24:40,740
I want to talk to him.

338
00:24:43,786 --> 00:24:45,309
It's okay, Bill.

339
00:24:50,532 --> 00:24:52,534
What's the problem, Pat?

340
00:24:52,578 --> 00:24:54,101
Hi angel.

341
00:24:56,320 --> 00:24:58,235
Hi, daddy.

342
00:24:59,715 --> 00:25:00,760
What do you want?

343
00:25:01,848 --> 00:25:03,284
I want you to come home.

344
00:25:06,592 --> 00:25:08,724
Already been there.

345
00:25:08,768 --> 00:25:11,248
Tommy, for God's sake.
I don't have any money.

346
00:25:11,292 --> 00:25:13,207
I don't even have any food...

347
00:25:13,250 --> 00:25:16,253
-Pat, I will help you out when
I get back on my feet, okay?
-What about

348
00:25:16,297 --> 00:25:20,475
the baby? And Christine,
she adores you.

349
00:25:20,519 --> 00:25:23,434
You're just gonna
run out on her?

350
00:25:23,478 --> 00:25:25,611
-Want some ice cream, honey?
-Where are you going?

351
00:25:25,654 --> 00:25:27,656
-Taking them away from you, Pat.
-What?

352
00:25:27,700 --> 00:25:29,876
You think I want her
to grow up
to be like you, huh?

353
00:25:29,919 --> 00:25:32,095
Get in the car, doll.
I'll get some ice cream.
Come on.

354
00:25:32,139 --> 00:25:34,054
-Tommy.
-I'm taking her away from you.

355
00:25:34,097 --> 00:25:37,187
-I'm gonna get custody, and you
ain't never gonna see her again!
-Stop it!

356
00:25:37,884 --> 00:25:38,885
Stop this.

357
00:25:39,538 --> 00:25:40,843
[CHILD CRYING]

358
00:25:40,887 --> 00:25:43,193
Christine, open the door honey.

359
00:25:43,237 --> 00:25:46,675
Sweetheart, open the door.
Honey, open the door!

360
00:25:46,719 --> 00:25:50,505
Tommy. Stop it! Stop it!

361
00:25:50,549 --> 00:25:52,594
[CAR SCREECHING]

362
00:25:55,858 --> 00:25:57,077
[CAR SCREECHING]

363
00:25:59,296 --> 00:26:00,820
What are you gonna do?

364
00:26:00,863 --> 00:26:02,561
I'm gonna call the police!

365
00:26:03,562 --> 00:26:04,563
[CAR SCREECHING]

366
00:26:13,963 --> 00:26:17,314
-We just went for a little ride.
-PATSY: A little ride?

367
00:26:17,358 --> 00:26:18,577
This time.

368
00:26:20,404 --> 00:26:21,797
PATSY: Give her to me!

369
00:26:21,841 --> 00:26:25,192
Gimme her!
Christine! Give her to me.

370
00:26:25,235 --> 00:26:27,107
[GASPING] Tommy!

371
00:26:27,150 --> 00:26:29,892
Don't you ever do that again!

372
00:26:29,936 --> 00:26:31,154
Ever!

373
00:26:33,983 --> 00:26:37,726
[SOBBING] Oh. God.

374
00:26:39,423 --> 00:26:42,165
Oh. How are we gonna live?

375
00:26:48,258 --> 00:26:50,478
Don't worry about it, Pat.

376
00:26:50,521 --> 00:26:53,524
Look, your folks will help
out, until I can kick in.

377
00:26:55,222 --> 00:26:57,093
Pat, you're not going to starve.

378
00:27:01,707 --> 00:27:03,273
Daddy loves you, honey.

379
00:27:07,277 --> 00:27:08,278
Hey, Bill!

380
00:27:25,469 --> 00:27:26,775
Oh!

381
00:27:34,174 --> 00:27:35,654
[GASPING]

382
00:27:43,444 --> 00:27:45,054
[BABY CRYING]

383
00:27:47,187 --> 00:27:48,231
Yes.

384
00:27:51,365 --> 00:27:53,236
My baby. My baby.

385
00:27:57,632 --> 00:27:58,633
[PATSY CHUCKLES]

386
00:28:04,030 --> 00:28:06,597
[BABY CRYING]

387
00:28:11,472 --> 00:28:12,908
[FOOTSTEPS APPROACHING]

388
00:28:14,301 --> 00:28:15,302
Pat?

389
00:28:17,783 --> 00:28:18,914
Tommy.

390
00:28:20,046 --> 00:28:21,221
What was it?

391
00:28:22,396 --> 00:28:23,658
It's a girl.

392
00:28:26,661 --> 00:28:27,706
Another one?

393
00:28:31,057 --> 00:28:33,015
Did you name her?

394
00:28:33,059 --> 00:28:35,322
You picked the
other girls' names.

395
00:28:37,628 --> 00:28:39,021
Do you wanna name her?

396
00:28:41,284 --> 00:28:43,504
Why don't you just err,

397
00:28:43,547 --> 00:28:45,419
pick one out of the phone book.

398
00:28:49,249 --> 00:28:50,685
[SIGHS WEARILY]

399
00:28:52,121 --> 00:28:53,514
Why are you here?

400
00:28:54,602 --> 00:28:57,213
-See what you had.
-We had, Tommy.

401
00:28:58,562 --> 00:28:59,825
We had.

402
00:29:02,915 --> 00:29:04,525
Did you know we're on welfare?

403
00:29:08,181 --> 00:29:10,357
Did you hear me?

404
00:29:10,400 --> 00:29:13,142
Your children and I,
are on welfare.

405
00:29:14,361 --> 00:29:15,841
How does that make you feel?

406
00:29:16,667 --> 00:29:17,756
Where's Christine?

407
00:29:19,888 --> 00:29:22,325
She and Andrea,
are with my folks.

408
00:29:24,501 --> 00:29:25,764
Well...

409
00:29:26,852 --> 00:29:28,462
I guess that's it then.

410
00:29:44,086 --> 00:29:46,219
There she is.

411
00:29:46,262 --> 00:29:50,266
[VOICE OVER PA SYSTEM] <i>
Attention. Visiting hours will</i><i>
be over in 15 minutes.</i>

412
00:29:51,790 --> 00:29:53,095
Oh, my God.

413
00:29:55,358 --> 00:29:56,838
Sweetheart.

414
00:29:56,882 --> 00:29:58,797
Hi, baby. How you doing huh?

415
00:29:59,754 --> 00:30:00,886
Ah, good.

416
00:30:02,757 --> 00:30:03,976
Patsy...

417
00:30:05,020 --> 00:30:06,282
Look, hon. Uh...

418
00:30:06,326 --> 00:30:08,371
What do you say we
take a little walk, okay?

419
00:30:08,415 --> 00:30:10,896
-You want to see her?
-Of course. Yes, yes.

420
00:30:12,288 --> 00:30:15,291
She looks just like Christine
when she was born.

421
00:30:15,335 --> 00:30:17,946
-You remember?
-Yeah.

422
00:30:17,990 --> 00:30:20,731
[OVER PA SYSTEM] Doctor Bartman,
please report to Radiology.

423
00:30:22,603 --> 00:30:24,083
<i>Doctor Bartman...</i>

424
00:30:25,519 --> 00:30:27,564
Honey, I want you
to sit over here.

425
00:30:27,608 --> 00:30:29,871
Oh, I'd be happy to.

426
00:30:29,915 --> 00:30:30,916
Careful.

427
00:30:33,005 --> 00:30:34,920
-You all right?
-Yeah.

428
00:30:35,746 --> 00:30:38,053
Uh,

429
00:30:38,097 --> 00:30:39,881
Tommy's gone.
He took everything.

430
00:30:40,969 --> 00:30:41,970
What?

431
00:30:43,232 --> 00:30:45,365
He emptied out your
bank account.

432
00:30:45,408 --> 00:30:48,847
He defaulted on the car loan,
and they repossessed it.

433
00:30:48,890 --> 00:30:51,762
-He even had
the phone disconnected.
-[PATSY GASPS]

434
00:30:51,806 --> 00:30:54,896
-There's nothing left.
-Oh, God.

435
00:30:54,940 --> 00:30:58,030
Oh, God, This can't be
happening. [SHUDDERS]

436
00:30:59,901 --> 00:31:01,729
How could he do that to us?

437
00:31:01,772 --> 00:31:04,688
Oh, honey, I'm so sorry.

438
00:31:05,646 --> 00:31:07,387
[GASPING]

439
00:31:09,606 --> 00:31:13,393
[MELANCHOLY MUSIC PLAYING]

440
00:31:14,002 --> 00:31:16,178
[BABIES CRYING]

441
00:31:21,575 --> 00:31:25,666
[SERENE INSTRUMENTAL
MUSIC PLAYING]

442
00:31:32,325 --> 00:31:33,674
That's my sister.

443
00:31:51,518 --> 00:31:55,957
[DRAMATIC MUSIC PLAYING]

444
00:32:08,404 --> 00:32:11,451
I keep telling you, Patsy,
it won't be so bad.

445
00:32:11,494 --> 00:32:14,802
-You'll get a job, you'll see.
-What kind of job?

446
00:32:14,845 --> 00:32:16,935
Well, maybe you could work
in the drugstore,

447
00:32:16,978 --> 00:32:19,285
in Harry's drugstore

448
00:32:19,328 --> 00:32:21,374
A couple of hours every day.

449
00:32:21,417 --> 00:32:24,986
Mom, I keep telling you.
I can't get a part time job.

450
00:32:25,030 --> 00:32:27,771
If I do that, I lose
my welfare benefits,

451
00:32:27,815 --> 00:32:31,079
and I make more on welfare,
than I would on a job like that.

452
00:32:31,123 --> 00:32:33,212
I'm just stuck.

453
00:32:33,255 --> 00:32:35,040
Now, don't talk like that.

454
00:32:35,083 --> 00:32:37,564
It's just a temporary thing.

455
00:32:37,607 --> 00:32:40,393
And there's no shame in taking
a little help, now and then.

456
00:32:41,568 --> 00:32:43,222
I just wish your dad
and I could help

457
00:32:43,265 --> 00:32:44,919
-some more.
-I know, ma.

458
00:32:47,617 --> 00:32:50,751
I just expected
more from my life.

459
00:32:50,794 --> 00:32:53,493
I'm not prepared for this.
I don't know how to do anything.

460
00:32:53,536 --> 00:32:56,365
I'm... I've no training. I...

461
00:32:56,409 --> 00:32:59,020
My life has come to a big
dead end, all of a sudden.

462
00:32:59,064 --> 00:33:00,630
I just wish...

463
00:33:02,415 --> 00:33:04,243
Wish I could go back to school.

464
00:33:05,070 --> 00:33:06,854
To school?

465
00:33:06,897 --> 00:33:09,422
You've got two years
of junior college.
Isn't that enough?

466
00:33:09,465 --> 00:33:13,121
No. I need to go back
for another two years
and get a degree.

467
00:33:13,165 --> 00:33:15,863
Maybe then I could
get a decent job,

468
00:33:15,906 --> 00:33:18,083
and I could support my kids.

469
00:33:19,693 --> 00:33:21,608
You really want this,
don't you?

470
00:33:21,651 --> 00:33:24,132
Yeah, I do. I
really, really do.

471
00:33:26,700 --> 00:33:28,484
I don't know...

472
00:33:28,528 --> 00:33:31,009
I mean, I don't even
know if they'll let me
go to school on welfare.

473
00:33:32,619 --> 00:33:34,447
Besides, what would
I do with the kids?

474
00:33:35,491 --> 00:33:36,710
Honey,

475
00:33:37,493 --> 00:33:39,495
what are grandmothers for?

476
00:33:40,931 --> 00:33:42,803
Would you take care
of them sometimes?

477
00:33:43,630 --> 00:33:45,284
Of course I would.

478
00:33:47,503 --> 00:33:48,939
You're still my baby.

479
00:33:53,031 --> 00:33:54,554
Ma, I'm so scared.

480
00:33:55,642 --> 00:33:57,296
I know, sweetheart.

481
00:33:57,731 --> 00:33:58,775
I know.

482
00:34:03,476 --> 00:34:05,695
Look, the Welfare Department
has never supported

483
00:34:05,739 --> 00:34:07,784
the idea of a recipient
going to college.

484
00:34:07,828 --> 00:34:09,308
Why not?

485
00:34:09,351 --> 00:34:12,006
What's wrong with wanting
to do something with my life?

486
00:34:12,050 --> 00:34:15,575
If you go back to school,
we have no way of knowing
where your money's going.

487
00:34:15,618 --> 00:34:20,884
The only chance that I have,
of getting off of welfare,
is to go back to school.

488
00:34:22,234 --> 00:34:25,150
Look, I'm... I'm not
getting child support.

489
00:34:25,193 --> 00:34:27,326
I don't think I ever will.

490
00:34:27,369 --> 00:34:30,720
[SIGHS] My husband hasn't
paid me a dime. I don't
even know where he is.

491
00:34:31,765 --> 00:34:32,896
I don't know.

492
00:34:32,940 --> 00:34:35,247
Why don't you make
me a test case?

493
00:34:38,598 --> 00:34:41,122
Nobody's ever asked this before.

494
00:34:41,166 --> 00:34:45,431
Please. I just want to
be able to take care of
myself and my family.

495
00:34:45,474 --> 00:34:47,433
Doesn't that count for anything?

496
00:34:47,476 --> 00:34:50,523
I don't think my supervisor
would approve this.

497
00:34:50,566 --> 00:34:52,090
Ask.

498
00:34:52,133 --> 00:34:54,570
Just ask. Okay?

499
00:34:57,182 --> 00:34:58,705
I'll think about it.

500
00:35:01,316 --> 00:35:02,317
Thank you.

501
00:35:17,027 --> 00:35:23,251
[SOMBER INSTRUMENTAL
MUSIC PLAYING]

502
00:35:34,654 --> 00:35:36,873
[INAUDIBLE]

503
00:36:00,245 --> 00:36:02,856
[PHONE RINGING]

504
00:36:19,220 --> 00:36:21,266
[PHONE RINGING]

505
00:36:56,344 --> 00:36:58,085
Good one.

506
00:36:58,128 --> 00:37:01,262
-Whoop!
-Pat! Pat! Jerry, wait.

507
00:37:01,915 --> 00:37:02,916
PATSY: Jerry!

508
00:37:11,620 --> 00:37:13,274
[EXCLAIMS]

509
00:37:13,318 --> 00:37:14,928
-Open it.
-I can't! I can't!

510
00:37:16,408 --> 00:37:18,975
[EXCLAIMING IN JOY]

511
00:37:19,019 --> 00:37:21,108
And the winner is...

512
00:37:22,370 --> 00:37:24,416
PATSY: I can't believe
it's straight A's!

513
00:37:24,459 --> 00:37:27,027
[ALL CHEERING]

514
00:37:32,424 --> 00:37:37,429
-[CROWD CLAPPING]
-[TRIUMPHANT INSTRUMENTAL
MUSIC PLAYING]

515
00:38:05,195 --> 00:38:07,023
RUTH: <i>Welcome to the IRS.</i>

516
00:38:07,067 --> 00:38:11,419
Now, the coffee boy is
the most important person
to know, of course.

517
00:38:11,463 --> 00:38:14,466
and you'll get your manuals
later on this afternoon.

518
00:38:15,815 --> 00:38:17,338
Let me introduce you to Grace.

519
00:38:17,382 --> 00:38:19,035
-Hi.
-Bob, Julie.

520
00:38:19,079 --> 00:38:20,385
-This is Pat.
-Hi.

521
00:38:20,428 --> 00:38:21,995
-Hi, Pat.
-Any questions?

522
00:38:22,038 --> 00:38:24,258
I don't think so.

523
00:38:24,302 --> 00:38:26,739
Now, you'll start here,
and you'll work your way, all
the way down there to the end.

524
00:38:26,782 --> 00:38:30,090
-To an office?
-Hard work. Dedication.
It's yours if you want it.

525
00:38:31,309 --> 00:38:32,571
Welcome aboard.

526
00:38:32,614 --> 00:38:33,963
Thanks, Ruth.

527
00:38:34,007 --> 00:38:36,009
-But let me know if
you need anything.
-I will.

528
00:38:36,052 --> 00:38:37,271
Good luck, Pat.

529
00:38:42,058 --> 00:38:46,193
[FAIRGROUND MUSIC PLAYING]

530
00:38:49,588 --> 00:38:50,763
Ooh!

531
00:38:57,596 --> 00:38:59,728
Hey! There they are.

532
00:39:01,208 --> 00:39:03,341
-Thank you.
-Christine is having a ball.

533
00:39:03,384 --> 00:39:06,735
-Did you see who's here?
Eddie's Lin and Uncle Crankwood
-I was so surprised.

534
00:39:06,779 --> 00:39:08,868
-Do you have some cake?
-It was wonderful.

535
00:39:08,911 --> 00:39:10,522
Oh, good.

536
00:39:10,565 --> 00:39:13,176
-Hi, Lorraine!
-Pat, free cake.
Where'd you get it?

537
00:39:13,220 --> 00:39:15,222
-I made it.
-Come on.

538
00:39:15,265 --> 00:39:17,529
Who taught her everything
she knew?

539
00:39:17,572 --> 00:39:20,053
[EXCITED CHATTERING]

540
00:39:22,447 --> 00:39:23,622
-Looks good.
-Yes.

541
00:39:25,014 --> 00:39:27,582
LORRAINE: Oh, it's terrific.
I love it.

542
00:39:27,626 --> 00:39:29,671
So good to see you
laughing again.

543
00:39:29,715 --> 00:39:32,761
Yeah, we're still broke,
but it's a start.

544
00:39:32,805 --> 00:39:34,415
[GATE OPENING]

545
00:39:36,852 --> 00:39:38,463
There's Bill.

546
00:39:39,768 --> 00:39:41,553
What's he doing here?

547
00:39:50,344 --> 00:39:52,607
Hi, Bill.

548
00:39:52,651 --> 00:39:55,697
-Pat, I'm sorry to interrupt
your party like this...
-Well, what is it?

549
00:39:57,351 --> 00:39:58,613
It's about Tommy.

550
00:40:00,180 --> 00:40:01,921
What about him?

551
00:40:03,749 --> 00:40:05,925
He came back, didn't he?

552
00:40:06,969 --> 00:40:09,798
Bill, did he? Is he back?

553
00:40:12,366 --> 00:40:13,759
No, Pat.

554
00:40:15,325 --> 00:40:16,979
Tommy's dead.

555
00:40:29,035 --> 00:40:31,472
How did it happen?

556
00:40:31,516 --> 00:40:33,822
Tommy's foster mother
called me this morning.

557
00:40:35,084 --> 00:40:37,304
-He was killed in a plane crash.
-Oh, my God.

558
00:40:38,131 --> 00:40:39,698
[SOBBING] Where?

559
00:40:41,787 --> 00:40:43,441
I don't know exactly.

560
00:40:52,145 --> 00:40:55,235
A friend of Tommy's in Atlanta,
phoned the Griffins.

561
00:40:58,020 --> 00:40:59,718
Are they sending him back here?

562
00:41:02,590 --> 00:41:03,983
They haven't found the body.

563
00:41:04,853 --> 00:41:06,507
-Oh.
-[CHRISTINE CRIES]

564
00:41:07,508 --> 00:41:08,466
It's all right, honey.

565
00:41:09,684 --> 00:41:11,991
-[CRIES]
-Sshhh.

566
00:41:13,819 --> 00:41:17,170
[CRIES BITTERLY]

567
00:41:24,394 --> 00:41:26,745
Oh, there you are.
Girl, I was looking for you.

568
00:41:27,572 --> 00:41:29,443
Your exemption case is here.

569
00:41:29,487 --> 00:41:31,793
Divorced mother.
She's got proof she was
the sole support of the child.

570
00:41:31,837 --> 00:41:33,969
Okay, great. I'll be with her
as soon as I can.

571
00:41:34,013 --> 00:41:36,537
[CHUCKLES] Girl, it's been
like that all day.

572
00:41:37,059 --> 00:41:38,452
Hello?

573
00:41:38,496 --> 00:41:41,107
LADY OVER THE PHONE: <i>
Mrs. Thomas Griffin, please.</i>

574
00:41:41,150 --> 00:41:43,849
-This is she. <i>
-This is Blanche Payton.</i>

575
00:41:43,892 --> 00:41:47,113
<i>I got your name and number</i><i>
from my husband's sister.</i>

576
00:41:47,156 --> 00:41:49,507
<i>I need to speak with you.</i><i>
It's about your ex-husband.</i>

577
00:41:50,725 --> 00:41:51,726
What do you want?

578
00:41:52,640 --> 00:41:53,641
I...

579
00:41:55,164 --> 00:41:57,210
Look, I don't have to say this,
but I think...

580
00:41:57,253 --> 00:41:59,342
<i>that the man I married</i><i>
seven months ago</i><i>
is your husband.</i>

581
00:42:00,822 --> 00:42:02,563
My husband is dead.

582
00:42:02,607 --> 00:42:04,913
He died in a plane crash
more than three years ago.

583
00:42:04,957 --> 00:42:06,872
<i>I don't think he's dead.</i>

584
00:42:06,915 --> 00:42:09,091
<i>His sister's name is Carol.</i>

585
00:42:09,135 --> 00:42:10,353
<i>She told me how to find you.</i>

586
00:42:11,616 --> 00:42:13,443
Where are you?

587
00:42:13,487 --> 00:42:15,489
<i>I'm at a pay phone</i><i>
at a restaurant</i><i>
called Birdie's.</i>

588
00:42:17,404 --> 00:42:19,145
-On Fourth? <i>
-Yes.</i>

589
00:42:21,016 --> 00:42:22,322
I'll be right there.

590
00:42:38,730 --> 00:42:40,296
Mrs. Griffin.

591
00:42:40,340 --> 00:42:42,603
Bennett, it's Pat Bennett.

592
00:42:42,647 --> 00:42:44,866
-Bennett?
-My maiden name.

593
00:42:52,134 --> 00:42:53,832
I met him a year ago.

594
00:42:53,875 --> 00:42:57,183
He told me his name was
John Douglas Payton.

595
00:42:57,226 --> 00:42:59,751
My husband's name was Griffin.

596
00:42:59,794 --> 00:43:00,839
Thomas Griffin.

597
00:43:00,882 --> 00:43:02,014
He lied to me.

598
00:43:03,363 --> 00:43:05,844
We were only married
a short time.

599
00:43:05,887 --> 00:43:08,237
And then two weeks ago,
he walked out on me.

600
00:43:10,675 --> 00:43:12,372
Without a word, he just...

601
00:43:13,460 --> 00:43:15,462
He just left
and he didn't come back.

602
00:43:16,985 --> 00:43:19,771
Do you have a picture of him?

603
00:43:21,555 --> 00:43:23,601
No, I'm sorry.

604
00:43:23,644 --> 00:43:25,733
Well, how do I know
you're telling me the truth?

605
00:43:25,777 --> 00:43:27,517
How do I know this isn't
some kind of...

606
00:43:29,258 --> 00:43:31,957
scam to get money from me?

607
00:43:40,487 --> 00:43:42,358
He's all I had.

608
00:43:45,753 --> 00:43:48,974
Oh, I was so...
I was so crazy in love with him.

609
00:43:51,585 --> 00:43:53,848
He'd hold me and he'd tell me
stories about how...

610
00:43:55,241 --> 00:43:56,721
All he wanted was to fly.

611
00:43:57,809 --> 00:43:59,114
And be with me.

612
00:44:00,246 --> 00:44:02,030
Just him and me.
That's all he wanted.

613
00:44:03,379 --> 00:44:05,033
And I would've done anything.

614
00:44:05,077 --> 00:44:08,820
I would have been anything
he wanted me to be.

615
00:44:10,691 --> 00:44:12,693
How did you find me?

616
00:44:12,737 --> 00:44:16,479
I looked through his things
and I found his sister's
phone number in Miami.

617
00:44:16,523 --> 00:44:19,657
She told me that,
that he'd been married to you.

618
00:44:21,310 --> 00:44:24,052
And we thought that when
he ran out on me,

619
00:44:24,096 --> 00:44:25,663
that he might have
come back to you.

620
00:44:27,012 --> 00:44:30,755
So I was hoping that,

621
00:44:30,798 --> 00:44:33,845
I'd find him here, with you.

622
00:44:37,152 --> 00:44:38,327
You never divorced?

623
00:44:42,592 --> 00:44:44,029
We thought he was dead.

624
00:44:45,117 --> 00:44:47,902
Wait, you have,
you have children?

625
00:44:50,209 --> 00:44:51,210
Three.

626
00:44:55,605 --> 00:44:57,172
You have any pictures?

627
00:45:21,719 --> 00:45:23,372
He told me he didn't want any.

628
00:45:25,853 --> 00:45:26,854
Not with me.

629
00:45:34,122 --> 00:45:36,951
That son of a bitch.

630
00:45:37,822 --> 00:45:39,214
For three years...

631
00:45:39,258 --> 00:45:44,176
I have lived in the mourning
thinking he was dead.

632
00:45:44,219 --> 00:45:47,092
Thinking I would never have
a chance to see him again.

633
00:45:47,135 --> 00:45:50,704
Never have a chance to confront
him with any of this.

634
00:45:51,879 --> 00:45:53,968
Now, I find out he's alive,

635
00:45:54,012 --> 00:45:57,015
but my girls still don't have
their father.

636
00:45:57,058 --> 00:46:00,322
What kind of man does this
to his family?

637
00:46:00,366 --> 00:46:02,107
Well, you know what I think
of him?

638
00:46:03,108 --> 00:46:04,500
Are you going to
tell the girls?

639
00:46:04,544 --> 00:46:07,460
No, I am not going to tell them.

640
00:46:07,503 --> 00:46:09,854
You're going to let them think
that he's still dead.

641
00:46:09,897 --> 00:46:12,813
Lorraine, I don't want them
hurt again.

642
00:46:14,772 --> 00:46:17,687
All these years,
he has manipulated me.

643
00:46:17,731 --> 00:46:22,954
Every time I cry, I thought
my heart would break, he won.

644
00:46:22,997 --> 00:46:26,653
Every time my girls were alone
and hungry, he won.

645
00:46:26,696 --> 00:46:29,177
I am not gonna let him win
anymore.

646
00:46:29,221 --> 00:46:31,789
I am going to take back my life.

647
00:46:37,533 --> 00:46:39,231
Why me? Why me?

648
00:46:39,274 --> 00:46:40,841
I don't need this in my life.

649
00:46:40,885 --> 00:46:41,886
This is disgusting.

650
00:46:41,929 --> 00:46:44,062
-It's... Woah!
-[CHUCKLES]

651
00:46:44,105 --> 00:46:46,455
What are you doing?

652
00:46:46,499 --> 00:46:48,980
It's my Saturday.
I really don't want to be here.

653
00:46:49,023 --> 00:46:51,721
Take the rake, and rake it
and put it in the bag.

654
00:46:51,765 --> 00:46:53,114
CHRISTINE: Mother!

655
00:46:54,028 --> 00:46:56,117
Mom, Lorraine is on the phone.

656
00:46:56,161 --> 00:46:58,293
Christine!
Lorraine, I'll call you back.

657
00:46:58,337 --> 00:46:59,512
She'll call you back.

658
00:46:59,555 --> 00:47:01,209
Christine, the phone is not
gonna reach.

659
00:47:01,253 --> 00:47:02,515
Think a little bit.

660
00:47:02,558 --> 00:47:04,169
[CAR HONKS]

661
00:47:04,212 --> 00:47:06,432
PAT: Come on,
just keep raking all right.

662
00:47:07,259 --> 00:47:09,696
Bye, mom. See ya later.

663
00:47:09,739 --> 00:47:11,002
Where are you going?

664
00:47:11,045 --> 00:47:14,396
-She's going with Tony.
-Tony?

665
00:47:14,440 --> 00:47:17,095
Tony. You know...
[LAUGHS LOFTILY]

666
00:47:17,138 --> 00:47:19,662
Mom, do I wash this in
whites or darks?

667
00:47:19,706 --> 00:47:21,055
Because this isn't dark.

668
00:47:21,099 --> 00:47:23,275
No, honey. Not white. Not dark.
They're colors.

669
00:47:23,318 --> 00:47:24,929
That pink goes with the colors.

670
00:47:24,972 --> 00:47:26,582
Okay, I'll do it.

671
00:47:34,286 --> 00:47:36,462
Okay, bye, honey.
See ya later.

672
00:47:45,471 --> 00:47:47,777
[BELL RINGING]

673
00:47:50,345 --> 00:47:51,433
[TYPING]

674
00:47:51,477 --> 00:47:52,478
[PHONE RINGING]

675
00:47:53,479 --> 00:47:54,523
Hello.

676
00:47:54,567 --> 00:47:56,134
WOMAN ON PHONE: <i>Mrs. Bennett?</i>

677
00:47:56,177 --> 00:47:58,223
-Yes, this is Miss Bennett. <i>
-About your daughter Marcia.</i>

678
00:47:58,963 --> 00:48:00,094
Yes?

679
00:48:00,138 --> 00:48:01,922
<i>This is Miss Campbell</i><i>
at her school.</i>

680
00:48:01,966 --> 00:48:04,577
<i>Marcia has been truant for</i><i>
three straight days.</i>

681
00:48:04,620 --> 00:48:05,970
<i>And it's not the first time.</i>

682
00:48:06,013 --> 00:48:07,449
<i>I think you'd better</i><i>
come over here.</i>

683
00:48:11,976 --> 00:48:12,977
[DOOR OPENS]

684
00:48:15,544 --> 00:48:17,416
[DOOR CLOSES]

685
00:48:17,459 --> 00:48:19,940
Well, why haven't I heard
about this before?
Why haven't you called me?

686
00:48:19,984 --> 00:48:21,986
If you look through her file,
you'll find...

687
00:48:22,029 --> 00:48:25,467
dozens of written excuses
forged in your name.

688
00:48:25,511 --> 00:48:26,555
Oh, she wouldn't do that.

689
00:48:26,599 --> 00:48:27,687
But she did.

690
00:48:27,730 --> 00:48:28,862
That's her pattern.

691
00:48:32,692 --> 00:48:34,346
What are you saying?

692
00:48:34,389 --> 00:48:35,825
I'm saying Marcia needs help.

693
00:48:36,652 --> 00:48:38,350
What kind of help?

694
00:48:38,393 --> 00:48:41,396
We have a program for kids like
Marcia who need more attention.

695
00:48:41,440 --> 00:48:45,226
I recommend that we transfer her
to a special class,

696
00:48:45,270 --> 00:48:46,836
but I need your approval.

697
00:48:49,013 --> 00:48:49,970
[DOOR OPENS]

698
00:49:10,599 --> 00:49:13,298
Just, what in the hell
is going on here?

699
00:49:13,341 --> 00:49:15,517
Have you ever wondered
why Marcia ditches school?

700
00:49:15,561 --> 00:49:17,432
Why Christine never goes out?

701
00:49:17,476 --> 00:49:20,000
Or why Andrea can't even keep
a boyfriend
for more than a few weeks.

702
00:49:20,044 --> 00:49:21,871
-Christine!
-Tell her.

703
00:49:22,960 --> 00:49:25,875
Yes, tell me.

704
00:49:25,919 --> 00:49:31,185
Well, I guess I feel like
I'm not good enough to like him,

705
00:49:31,229 --> 00:49:33,405
and then I just suffocate
whoever it is I'm with.

706
00:49:35,102 --> 00:49:36,538
And then, what?

707
00:49:37,713 --> 00:49:38,758
They leave.

708
00:49:40,238 --> 00:49:41,239
Honey.

709
00:49:43,632 --> 00:49:46,940
You don't have to do that
to keep a boy.

710
00:49:46,984 --> 00:49:51,336
I know, but, I just get
so panicky.

711
00:49:53,468 --> 00:49:55,949
CHRISTINE: Have you ever read
any of Marcia's poetry?

712
00:49:55,993 --> 00:49:57,603
Poetry?

713
00:49:57,646 --> 00:50:00,823
She writes about pain
and wishing she was never born.

714
00:50:03,739 --> 00:50:05,959
Oh, honey. Marcia.

715
00:50:09,267 --> 00:50:10,268
Is that true?

716
00:50:11,834 --> 00:50:12,835
Oh, honey.

717
00:50:17,579 --> 00:50:20,060
I've always tried to be there
for you girls.

718
00:50:21,018 --> 00:50:23,411
I think we needed a father, too.

719
00:50:23,455 --> 00:50:26,240
You never let anyone get
close enough to take his place.

720
00:50:27,546 --> 00:50:29,983
Dad really messed us up, Mom.

721
00:50:30,027 --> 00:50:32,551
I never even knew you thought
about him.

722
00:50:32,594 --> 00:50:34,727
CHRISTINE: Yeah.

723
00:50:34,770 --> 00:50:37,643
Yeah, it's like this family
should come with its own
warning label. "No men allowed."

724
00:50:41,081 --> 00:50:42,865
MBA and promotion.

725
00:50:42,909 --> 00:50:44,041
How does it feel?

726
00:50:46,869 --> 00:50:47,870
Good.

727
00:50:50,960 --> 00:50:53,093
-Feels good.
-Uh oh.

728
00:50:53,137 --> 00:50:54,442
What's going on with you?

729
00:50:55,052 --> 00:50:56,792
It's my kids.

730
00:50:59,752 --> 00:51:01,667
Marcia is in all kinds
of trouble at school,

731
00:51:01,710 --> 00:51:03,451
and I never even knew about it.

732
00:51:03,495 --> 00:51:04,496
And Andrea...

733
00:51:07,368 --> 00:51:09,762
I don't think I ever really
realized the effect

734
00:51:09,805 --> 00:51:11,981
not having a father
has had on them.

735
00:51:12,025 --> 00:51:13,766
You've done your best, honey.

736
00:51:13,809 --> 00:51:15,463
Kids get into trouble.

737
00:51:15,507 --> 00:51:17,378
Even in the best of families.
It happens.

738
00:51:17,422 --> 00:51:19,380
On top of everything else,
I get a letter

739
00:51:19,424 --> 00:51:21,034
rejecting my request for Tommy's

740
00:51:21,078 --> 00:51:24,472
social security death benefits
for the girls.

741
00:51:24,516 --> 00:51:27,301
They say, I can't collect, even
though nobody has heard from him

742
00:51:27,345 --> 00:51:29,129
-for more than ten years.
-But why not?

743
00:51:29,173 --> 00:51:31,436
I thought the state of Virginia
declared him legally dead.

744
00:51:31,479 --> 00:51:33,002
They did. Doesn't mean anything.

745
00:51:33,046 --> 00:51:36,049
Just makes his disappearance
legal.

746
00:51:36,093 --> 00:51:39,183
He's out there, Ruth.
He is out there.

747
00:51:43,230 --> 00:51:44,449
I'm gonna try and find him.

748
00:51:46,146 --> 00:51:48,627
I'm gonna make him answer
to those girls.

749
00:51:49,454 --> 00:51:50,933
They're entitled to that.

750
00:51:50,977 --> 00:51:52,457
They're entitled to
child support.

751
00:51:52,500 --> 00:51:55,286
After all he's done, that is the
least he could give them.

752
00:51:55,329 --> 00:51:57,549
Take it easy, girlfriend.
Now, you deserve a break.

753
00:51:58,811 --> 00:52:00,595
Why don't we celebrate your
promotion?

754
00:52:00,639 --> 00:52:02,075
I've been given two tickets

755
00:52:02,119 --> 00:52:05,426
to Congressman Henderson's
fundraiser, this Saturday.

756
00:52:05,470 --> 00:52:07,602
-We're going.
-Ruth, I don't...

757
00:52:07,646 --> 00:52:10,562
Every eligible man
on Capitol Hill will be there.

758
00:52:10,605 --> 00:52:12,085
It'll be fun.

759
00:52:12,129 --> 00:52:13,304
You owe it to yourself.

760
00:52:18,700 --> 00:52:19,701
Saturday.

761
00:52:22,226 --> 00:52:28,754
[PLAYING HARP]

762
00:52:39,156 --> 00:52:41,070
Some nice-looking men here,
don't you think?

763
00:52:41,114 --> 00:52:44,770
-Ruth, stop!
-I just want you to be happy.

764
00:52:44,813 --> 00:52:47,990
-Please.
-Mingle. Talk to people.

765
00:52:48,034 --> 00:52:50,341
Why don't you talk to that
nice, young man over there?

766
00:52:52,691 --> 00:52:54,171
Good to see you again.

767
00:53:03,919 --> 00:53:06,052
